<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Writ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">ten evidence from Tim Bartlett (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">PH 26</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Complaints: do they make a difference?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.89pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">What objectives should Ministers adopt when considering how complaints about Government and about public services provided by Government are handled?</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">What gaps in the complaints systems exist; and how should ministers ensure they are addressed?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Things can look very different when viewed from different perspectives. Senior civil servants may genuinely believe that their departments/agencies are doing a good job of dealing with complaints simply because those lower down the pecking order are able to tick off boxes as "resolved", while members of the public are left frustrated because genuine grievances have been stonewalled so persistently that they have been forced to give up.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">I suggest that no complaint can be regarded as "resolved" until the person who made the complaint is satisfied with the outcome. Whilst this may mean that some complaints can never be resolved, it would be considerably better than the present system in which genuine grievances are ignored. </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.89pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How effectively do Government departments and public service providers use </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">complaints to improve the service provided?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Government departments and public service providers do not appear to use </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">complaints to improve the service provided</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">, and seem to have </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">little or no</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> incentive to do so.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Who should be accountable for leadership and governance of complaints systems across government and its agencies?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No comment</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How should data on complaints be gathered and monitored?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No comment</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How should information about complaints be used to lead and drive </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">improvement?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No comment</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">What do complaints cost; and how much money could be saved by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">learning from complaints?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">I am submitting a separate document that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">refers to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> two complaints I have made that in the past five years that were eventually submitted to the Ombudsman. Both were all about money: in both cases, I am sure the officials concerned believe th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">at by stonewalling my complaints they were</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> "saving"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">public </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">money. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">In one case, defending myself against an unjustified demand for less than £150 cost me about £2000. I doubt whether it cost the agency concerned any less. The case was eventually settled (in my favour) in court, but I have no doubt that there are thousands of people who are less stub</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">born than I, who simply give up, so in pure financial terms, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">I am sure their strategy does, indeed "save" money.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The true cost of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">the stonewalling strategy </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">is in public trust. There is a limit to the number of times any individual can be expected to put up with arrogance and dishonesty from civil servants before they begin to believe</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">all (or most) civil servants are arrogant and dishonest and that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">dishonesty has be</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">en elevated to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">official policy.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.89pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How quickly do complaints systems deal with legitimate grievances and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">provide redress?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">They do not.</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.89pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How easy is it to make a complaint about a Government department or agency,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">and how could this be improved?</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Can people easily find their way around complaints systems?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No. Even if each individual step is clear, the procedure as a whole is not. Some officials seem to feel obliged to make it as difficult as possible to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">progress a complaint</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Do complaints systems provide proper access for vulnerable,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">disengaged, or excluded groups?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">I am</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> grammar-school educated, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">a former Royal Navy officer, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">now a journalist, so I regard myself as well-educated and literate. I have found dealing with government agencies to be difficult, time-consuming, and frustrating. How someone who is ill, frail, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">or has learning difficulties or a poor grasp of E</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">nglish would cope is unimaginable. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How welcome are complaints to government departments and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">agencies, compared to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">complaints to a department store or to a mobile phone company for example? What should government learn from the private sector?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">I do not believe any person or organisation welcomes complaints, but most private sector organisations recognise that the best way to deal with them is quickly and honestly. My experience of government agencies is the opposite: delays seem to be a deliberate strategy; mistakes are commonplace and deliberate misrepresentation is not unusual.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Do complaints systems succeed in making public services and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">government departments more accountable and responsive to service users?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No.</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.89pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Do complaints-handling systems achieve the right balance between nonjudicial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">and judicial investigations and remedies?</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">What is the right balance?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No. In my opinion, judicial investigation/remedy should be unnecessary in most cases: deliberate dishonesty should be extremely rare, and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">it should be possible to rectify </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">genuine mistakes without recourse to the judicial system. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">How can ministers reduce litigation costs and defensive behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">in favour of informal redress and openness?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Sadly, I believe the culture of "defensive behaviour" has progressed to the stage at which institutional dishonesty has become widespread and deeply ingrained: I refer you to the case histories outlined in the attached document. </span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.89pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How aware are service users of the various ombudsmen (such as the Local </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Government Ombudsman, Financial Ombudsman and the Housing Ombudsman)?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How do they coordinate their respective roles?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No comment</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.89pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">What lessons for complaints handling in the NHS are emerging from the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Francis Report into failing at Mid Staffordshire Hospital?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Which lessons have relevance to complaints handling processes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">elsewhere in Government and public services?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No comment</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.8pt; padding-left:5.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How well do Ministers and senior officials deal with complaints raised by MPs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">on behalf of constituents?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">What do Ministers and senior officials learn from complaints and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">how do they use complaints as feedback on departmental policy and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">implementation?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No comment</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.89pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How should complaints about complaints systems be handled?</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How should departments and government as a whole monitor </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">performance of complaints handling systems?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No comment</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Do tribunals systems work effectively; and how could they be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">improved?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">I have only one experience of a tribunal, and that was almost 20 years ago, against the CSA. The tribunal was merely another coat of whitewash over an unjustified decision</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">, and another hoop that I had to jump through before the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> matter was </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">eventually </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">resolved </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">by</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> the Social Security Commissioner.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Should there be a single point of contact for impartial information </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">on where to make a complaint or to seek redress? How should this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">be provided?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">In a perfect world, a "one-stop" shop -- analogous to UCAS for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">handling </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">applications to higher education</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> or the 999 telephone number for contacting the emergency services</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> -- would be ideal. But </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">unless and until government departments and agencies learn to deal with complaints properly, it would be a wasted effort.</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How do other countries handle complaints and what could the UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Government learn from them?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No comment</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Parliament’s Ombudsman Service</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">What should be the relationship between the Parliamentary and Health </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Service Ombudsman and;</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The individual citizen?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Parliament?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The Public Administration Select Committee?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">For many people, the Ombudsman is the final safety net to protect them against maladministration or deliberate wrong-doing by government officials. It should exercise that role responsibly, rather than treating complaints as a box-ticking exercise. It should certainly not be attempting to take on more complaints unless it is able and willing to investigate them properly, rather than finding excuses to dismiss them. The ombudsman's own figures show that less than 2% of complaints are investigated, and less than 1% are upheld. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The chances of the Ombudsman actually investigating any individual complaint are about the same as the chance of winning a prize in the National lottery with a single ticket</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">A "safety net" that allows more than 98% of cases to fall through it is not fit for purpose, and is probably beyond repair. It should be discarded, and an effective replacement introduced as soon as possible.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">I am not qualified to comment on the Ombudsman's relationship with Parliament or the PASC, except that as the Ombudsman </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">claims to have been "...</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> set up by Parliament to help both individuals and the public</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">.", it has a duty to Parliament to do what it was set up to do. Its own figures show that it is failing to investigate more than 98% of complaints submitted to it. I am sure a postman who dumped 98% of letters in the bin, or a bus driver who left 98% of his passengers standing at bus stops would soon find themselves looking for new jobs. I see no reason why the Ombudsman should continue to receive taxpayer's money for doing less than 2% of the job.</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How effective is the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman as a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">service for handling complaints that have not been adequately dealt with</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">elsewhere?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Useless. It is an exercise in whitewashing.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How should complaints about the Parliamentary and Health</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Service Ombudsman be handled? </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">How effectively does the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman deal with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">complaints?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">In my experience, the PHSO does not deal with complaints about itself.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> I received a letter that failed to address the fundamental issue I had raised, but whose concluding sentences were</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">"This review is the end of the complaints process, and it is time to draw correspondence on your complaint to a close. We will acknowledge anything more you send us about it, but will only respond if we see a need to."</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">I understand that this is standard practice, and that even the wording is virtually standard.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Should citizens have direct access to the Parliamentary and Health Service</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Ombudsman for all complaints, as people already have in respect of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">complaints about the NHS?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No. Such a move would probably increase the number of complaints submitted, but it is difficult to imagine that it would increase the number that are investigated and upheld. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">There is more </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">chance </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">winning a prize in the National lottery</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> than of getting the Ombudsman to investigate a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">complaint.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">In both my cases, the reasons given by the PHSO for refusing to investigate were inadequate.</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">one was untrue</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">one missed the point because it was based on PHSO's own inaccurate paraphrasing of the complaint.</span></li></ul><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The policy of not investigating cases that have "already been decided in court" means that agencies can buy immunity from investigation for the minimal price of a court fee. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The essential point of my complaint against the PCT/SHA was ignored so persistently that it is difficult to believe that it was accidental.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">In both my case histories, simple facts given in answer to direct questions on the PHSO complaint form were ignored. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Correspondence received from the PHSO is arrogant and condescending</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">'s operation is completely opaque: it did not tell me what evidence it had received, considered, or rejected, or give a rationale for its decisions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO seems determined to minimise contact with complainants. At review level, in particular, I suggest that face-to-face meetings might help to clarify complex issues. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO staff appear to have far more empathy with the civil servants they are supposed to be investigating than with the members of the public they are supposed to be protecting</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">According to the PHSO website</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">: "... our role is to investigate complaints that individuals have been treated unfairly or have received poor service from government departments and other public organisations and the NHS in England. We do this f</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">airly and without taking sides</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The reality is that:</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO is failing to investigate complaints</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">By dismissing the vast majority of complaints without proper investigation, PHSO is taking sides against complainants.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">By making decisions that fly in the face of available evidence, PHSO is acting unfairly.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO is not fit for purpose: it should be radically overhauled, or scrapped altogether.</span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></li></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 1: DVLA</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">In January 2008, I </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">sold my</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> car, and sent all the paperwork to DVLA. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">DVLA refunded the unexpired tax, but four months later it wrote to me claiming "arrears"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">of tax (on the vehicle that I no longer owned) and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">demanding a late payment penalty. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">DVLA subsequently accepted that I had disposed of the vehicle and dropped its claim for "arrears", but continued to demand the late payment penalty. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The Independent Complaints Assessor</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> advised</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">DVLA to let the matter drop, but DVLA persisted and eventually took the matter to the county court.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The court dismissed DVLA's case.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">My MP referred the matter to the Ombudsman. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">: Comments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The idea that a late payment penalty can be charged in respect of a debt that was never owed in the first place is clearly ludicrous. Nevertheless, DVLA has tried the same trick on countless other motorists. The practice has been featured in newspaper articles</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> and TV programmes</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">, but DVLA continues to "try it on", despite having lost so many court cases that it must know its actions have no legal foundation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">My complaint to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> pointed out that DVLA's performance targets require</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> it to collect at least 416,000 penalty payments per year</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">despite the fact that there we</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">re only 330,000 unlicensed vehicles in the UK</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> So </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">DVLA </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">could only meet its revenue targets by collecting unjustified penalties from thousands of innocent motorists.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I believe the issues I raised were of public interest because of the large number of similar cases, particularly as DVLA had recently been criticised by the Public Accounts Committee for supplying misleading information about the extent of Vehicle Excise Duty evasion.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 38.8pt; padding-left:0.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The form on which my complaint was submitted to PHSO included the question </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Have you taken, or are you planning to take, legal action?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">to which I had correctly answered "No".</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO refused to investigate this case on the grounds that my complaint had already been dealt with by a court.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 1: Conclusions</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The reason given by the PHSO for refusing to investigate my complaint was false because:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">the court had no remit to investigate the cause of DVLA's initial error or its motives for persisting in its demand.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I had not claimed against the DVLA to recover the costs and losses I had incurred so this aspect of the case was never considered by the court.</span></li></ul><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The policy of not investigating cases that have "already been decided in court" means that agencies can buy immunity from investigation for the minimal price of a court fee. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 2: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Primary Care Trust</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">This case concerns the funding of long-term health care. I appreciate that this is a sensitive issue, but my complaint was not about the rights or wrongs of government policy: it was concerned solely with whether the published policy was properly carried out. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">: Technical background</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The relevant procedures are laid down by the Department of Health in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">National Framework for NHS Continuing Healthcare and NHS-funded Nursing Care</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">NHS Continuing Healthcare Practice Guidance</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The National Framework requires that the patient's needs must be assessed by a Multid</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">isciplinary Team (MDT</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">). </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Para 81 of the National Framework 2009 </span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> says:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> PCTs should not</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> refer a case back</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> or</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> decide not to accept a recommendation simply because the multidisciplinary team has made a recommendation that differs from the one that those who are involved in making the final decision would have made</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">, based on the same evidence."</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.1pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Para 9.2 of t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">he Practice Guidance </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">says:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"PCT decision-making processes should not have the function of: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">financial gatekeeping </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">completing/altering DSTs</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">overturning recommendations (although they can refer cases back to an MDT for further work in certain circumstances – see below)." </span></li></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">: Narrative</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">In September 2009, my </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">father suffered a severe stroke</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> and was admitted to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">hospital. When </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">it was clear that he was unlikely to recover, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">he was</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> discharge</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">d to a nursing home.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">In January 2010, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">the Primary Care Trust </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">(PCT) wrote to say </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">it would not fund </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">my father's Continuing Health C</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I subsequently obtained a copy of the MDT's original report, and found that it differed significantly from the version sent to me by the PCT. In particular, it concluded that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">...</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> Mr </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">***</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> needs demonstrate a primary healthcare need </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">and a nursing home placement should be fully funded under continuing health care."</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I appealed to the PCT on the grounds that it should not have rewritten the DST and should not have overturned the MDT's recommendation. My appeal was rejected.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">case</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">was reviewed by the Strategic Health Authority (SHA) in June 2011.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The SHA rejected my appeal, so the matter was referred </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">to the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO in September 2011</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The PHSO</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">refused to investigate my complaint against the PCT on the grounds that the SHA had </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">conducted an appropriately detailed assessment, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">appropriately considered the National Framework and reached reasonable conclusions</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">"</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">In October 2012, the PHSO agree</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">d to review its decision, but in February 2013 wrote to me saying that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"Without any new evidence which we have not already considered, there is nothing in your review complaint that makes me think that our decision was wrong"</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 2: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The Ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">'s initial assessment</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I made it clear on the PHSO complaint form that the key issue was that the PCT had disobeyed explicit instructions contained in the National Framework. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">In its reply, the PHSO incorrectly paraphrased this as:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"You told us that the SHA failed to properly consider the discrepancies between the PCT's decision and the original Multi Disciplinary Team (the MDT) decision regarding your father's eligibility for Continuing Healthcare funding (CHC funding). Particularly that the PCT overturned the MDT decision that funding should be granted without providing any </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">proper explanation.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The inaccuracy is subtle but significant: it converts a question of fact</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">into a matter of opinion.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> "D</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">id the PCT disobey the para 81 of the National Framework and para 9.2 of the Practice Guidance?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal">became </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">W</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ere the explanations given by the PCT and SHA "proper" o</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">r reasonable? </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I presented documentary evidence showing that the PCT disobeyed the explicit instructions issued by the Department of Health in the National Framework and Practice Guidance by:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">rewording the findings recorded in the Decision Support Tool by the MDT</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">rejecting the recommendation of the MDT.</span></li></ul><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Contrary to the evidence presented to it, the PHSO's concluded that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"We consider that the SHA conducted an appropriately detailed assessment, appropriately considered the National Framework, which was the applicable standard at the time of your father's assessment, and reached reasonable conclusions based upon sufficiently detailed evidence.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">This is wrong, because if the SHA had "appropriately considered" the National Framework, it could not have failed to notice that the PCT had disobeyed the explicit instructions published by the Department of Health in the National Framework and Practice Guidance -- particularly as the relevant paragraphs had been pointed out to it!.</span></li></ul><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.1pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO made much of the opinions expressed by </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> "Clinical Adviser". In particular, it claimed that : </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"You considered that the PCT overturned the MDT recommendation without providing an explanation. We can see that a further letter was sent to you, which our Adviser is satisfied provides a reasonable explanation and details</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> of appropriate remedial action</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">."</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Again, it begins by misrepresenting my complaint.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The Adviser's opinion is irrelevant, because the National Framework and Practice Guidance do not allow a PCT to overturn the recommendation of an MDT merely because it disagrees with it, no matter how "reasonable" the explanation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">No "remedial" action was suggested or taken.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 2: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The Ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">'s review</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">My letter requesting PHSO to review its earlier decision reiterated the key point that the PCT had disobeyed the National Framework and that the SHA had failed to recognise and rectify that disobedience.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">In February 2013, I received a telephone call from PHSO. It came out of the blue, and seemed to serve no useful purpose:  I got the impression that it was made so that PHSO could "tick the box" to say it had talked to me, rather than with any intention of giving or receiving information.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I followed it up with an email re-stating the points that: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">the PCT is not authorised to overturn the recommendation of an MDT merely because it disagrees with it.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">there is no evidence to support the SHA's assertion that "</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The Primary Care trust followed the proc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ess correctly in line with the N</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ational Framework for Continuing Health Care."</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">  </span></li></ul><ol start="59" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">On 15 February 2013, PHSO wrote to me:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">claiming that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO could not look at the PCTs actions because my complaint against the PCT had already been heard by the SHA</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">repeating the assertion that my complaint was that the PCT had failed to explain its actions, rather than that its actions contravened the instructions given in the National Framework and Practice Guidance. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">saying </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Without </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">any new evidence </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">which we </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">not already considered, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">there </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">nothing in your review complaint </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">makes </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">me </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">think </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">decision was </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">wrong."</span></li></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Case History 2: Conclusions</span></p><ol start="60" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The reason given by the PHSO for its initial refusal to investigate my complaint against the PCT/SHA was unsatisfactory because:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO either misunderstood or misrepresented the most fundamental part of my complaint. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO's assertion that the SHA "appropriately considered the National Framework" is false.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> If the SHA had indeed considered the National Framework, it could not possibly have missed the significance of paragraphs 80-81 that I had repeatedly brought to its attention.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The opinion of PHSO's clinical adviser is irrelevant because the National Framework and Practice Guidance specifically preclude a PCT from overturning the recommendation of an MDT, even if the PCT disagrees with it.</span></li></ul><ol start="61" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The reason given by PHSO for its review decision not to investigate my complaint was unsatisfactory because:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">It claimed that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO could not look at the PCTs actions because my complaint against the PCT had already been heard by the SHA</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I have no doubt that if my complaint had </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">not</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> been referred to the SHA, PHSO would have refused to investigate on the grounds that the internal complaints procedure had not been completed.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Yet again, it failed to address the core reason for my complaint.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">It ignored the evidence presented to it</span></li></ul><ol start="62" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">PHSO has persistently ignored the single most important issue in my complaint against the PCT/SHA. PHSO has not refuted it, denied it, or even acknowledged it: it has simply ignored it, despite having it pointed out in:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">my initial complaint</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">the correspondence between myself and the PCT and SHA that accompanied my initial complaint</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">my reply to the PHSO's response to my initial complaint</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">my request for review</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">my email  to the official who carried out the review</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">my reply to the PHSO's final letter</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">When such a simple point is so persistently ignored, it becomes difficult to believe that it is due to simple oversight or honest misunderstanding.</span></li><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1.5pt; clear:both; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 17.3pt"></div><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The Department of Health directs that PCTs must not overturn the recommendation of MDTs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The PCT did exactly what </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">the DoH</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> told </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">not to do. </span></p></ul><ol start="63" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">One question on the PHSO complaint form asked how I would like the Ombudsman to communicate with me. I responded </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"email".</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I have never received a single email from the PHSO: the few communications I have received have been by telephone or letter.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">With hindsight, I regard this as typical of the contempt with which the PHSO treats its "customers".</span></li></ul><ol start="64" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">I found the concluding remarks in the PHSO's final letter condescending and unhelpful:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"Without </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">any new evidence </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">which we </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">have </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">not al</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ready considered, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">there </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">nothing in your</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> review compl</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">aint </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">makes </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">me </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">think </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">our </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">decision was </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">wrong. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">... </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> This </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">review </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">end </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">of the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">compl</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">aints </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">process, and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">it </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">time </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">draw </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">correspondence on </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">your </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">complaint </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">a close. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">We </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">will </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">acknowledge </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">anything </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">more you send </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">us </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">about </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">it, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">but will onl</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">y </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">respond </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">if </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">we </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">see </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">need </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">to."</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">It did not specify what evidence had been considered, what evidence had been rejected, what counter-evidence or arguments had been advanced by the PCT and SHA, nor did it explain the rationale for ignoring the documentary evidence provided.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.2pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">It seemed smug, self-satisfied, and dismissive. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Ombudsman</span></p><ol start="65" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.1pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">According to the Ombudsman's website:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Our role is to investigate complaints that individuals have been treated unfairly or have received poor service from government departments and other public organisations and the NHS in England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">We work to put things right where we can and to share lessons learned to improve public services.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">"</span></p><ol start="66" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">The following figures are collated from the PHSO's Annual Reports for 2009-10</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> and 2010-11</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 114.55pt; text-indent:-42.55pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 114.55pt; text-indent:-42.55pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Total Complaints</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-colla